2. Sidecar Container:
---------- --------

A Sidecar Container is a container that runs alongside the main application container in the same Pod.

Think of it like this:

Pod
├── Main Container (Application)
└── Sidecar Container (Helper)

Both containers:

Run at the same time
Share the same network (same Pod IP)
Can share the same volume
Start together and stop together

1.Examples
Shared Volume Example
volumes:
- name: shared-data
  emptyDir: {}

Mounted in both containers:
volumeMounts:
- name: shared-data
  mountPath: /shared

Both can access:
/shared

1.Simple Sidecar Demo:

vim Sidecar.yaml

apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: sidecar-demo

spec:
  volumes:
  - name: shared
    emptyDir: {}

  containers:

  - name: app
    image: busybox
    command:
    - sh
    - -c
    - |
      while true
      do
        date >> /shared/log.txt
        sleep 5
      done
    volumeMounts:
    - name: shared
      mountPath: /shared

  - name: sidecar
    image: busybox
    command:
    - sh
    - -c
    - |
      tail -f /shared/log.txt
    volumeMounts:
    - name: shared
      mountPath: /shared

Apply:
kubectl apply -f sidecar.yaml

Check pod:
kubectl get pods

Expected:
side-car-demo   2/2   Running

Notice 2/2 Running:
Container 1 = main-app
Container 2 = sidecar

Verify both containers:
kubectl describe pod side-car-demo

You should see:
Containers:
  main-app
  sidecar


Check logs from the sidecar:

View sidecar logs:
kubectl logs sidecar-demo -c sidecar

Output:
Mon Jun 15 06:10:01 UTC 2026
Mon Jun 15 06:10:06 UTC 2026
Mon Jun 15 06:10:11 UTC 2026

The main container writes timestamps into /shared/log.txt, and the sidecar continuously reads that file using tail -f.

This is a classic sidecar pattern: one container produces data, the other container consumes or processes it.
The sidecar is reading what the main container writes.

Interview Questions
What is a Sidecar Container?
A helper container that runs with the main application container in the same Pod and provides supporting functionality
such as logging, monitoring, proxying, configuration updates, or security.


Difference Between Init Container and Sidecar:
| Feature                  | Init Container            | Sidecar Container          |
| ------------------------ | ------------------------- | -------------------------- |
| Runs before app          | Yes                       | No                         |
| Runs with app            | No                        | Yes                        |
| Must finish successfully | Yes                       | No                         |
| Runs continuously        | No                        | Yes                        |
| Common use               | Setup, checks, migrations | Logging, monitoring, proxy |


Exam/Interview One-Line Answer
"A Sidecar Container is a helper container running in the same Pod as the application container, sharing network and storage,
and providing supporting services such as logging, monitoring, service mesh proxying, or configuration management."
